= content_for(:page_title) do
  Building Components

.prose
  :markdown
    # Building Your Own Components

    _Loco_**Motion** ships with dozens of ready-made components, but its real
    power is the DSL underneath them. When you can't find exactly what you need,
    build your own — parts, tags, CSS, and Stimulus controllers, all in one
    place.

    Every component you build inherits from `LocoMotion::BaseComponent` (usually
    through your app's `ApplicationComponent`), which gives you the same clean
    API the built-in components use.

    ## 1. Anatomy of a Component

    A component is a Ruby class paired with a HAML template. The class declares
    its **parts**, configures them in `before_render`, and the template renders
    them.

.mt-6.max-w-prose
  = doc_code(language: "ruby") do
    :plain
      # app/components/character_component.rb
      class CharacterComponent < ApplicationComponent
        define_parts :head, :body, :legs

        def before_render
          set_tag_name(:head, :h1)
          add_css(:head, "text-3xl font-bold")

          add_stimulus_controller(:body, "character-body")
        end
      end

.mt-6.max-w-prose
  = doc_code(language: "haml") do
    :plain
      -# app/components/character_component.html.haml
      = part(:component) do
        = part(:head) do
          = @name
        = part(:body) do
          = content
        = part(:legs)

.mt-6.prose
  :markdown
    ## 2. Parts

    A **part** is a configurable HTML element. Declare parts with `define_part`
    (or `define_parts` for several at once), then render them in the template
    with `part(:name)`.

    - `part(:component)` is always available — it is the root element, handled
      for you by `BaseComponent`. Never declare it yourself.
    - Every part automatically accepts `<name>_css` and `<name>_html` options,
      so callers can tweak any part without you writing extra code.

    Configure parts inside `before_render`:

    - `set_tag_name(:head, :h1)` — choose the element's HTML tag.
    - `add_css(:head, "text-3xl font-bold")` — append Tailwind / DaisyUI classes.
    - `add_html(:head, { title: "Hi!" })` — merge arbitrary HTML attributes.
    - `add_stimulus_controller(:body, "character-body")` — wire up a Stimulus
      controller.

    ## 3. Slots

    Slots let callers pass rich, structured content into your component. Declare
    them with ViewComponent's `renders_one` and `renders_many`:

.mt-6.max-w-prose
  = doc_code(language: "ruby") do
    :plain
      class CharacterComponent < ApplicationComponent
        renders_one :weapon, WeaponComponent
        renders_many :accessories
      end

.mt-6.prose
  :markdown
    Then render them in the template just like parts:

.mt-6.max-w-prose
  = doc_code(language: "haml") do
    :plain
      = part(:component) do
        - if weapon?
          = weapon
        - accessories.each do |accessory|
          = accessory

.mt-6.prose
  :markdown
    ## 4. Options

    Read caller-supplied options with `config_option`, which also lets you
    provide a default:

.mt-6.max-w-prose
  = doc_code(language: "ruby") do
    :plain
      def initialize(*args, **kws)
        super

        @name = config_option(:name, "Nameless Hero")
      end

.mt-6.prose
  :markdown
    Remember the LocoMotion convention: **don't** add `size:` or `color:`
    options. Callers apply DaisyUI classes directly through `css:` instead, so a
    single component works with every variant and theme.

    ## 5. Using Your Component

    Render your component from any view — pass options, fill slots, and provide
    the main content as a block:

.mt-6.max-w-prose
  = doc_code(language: "haml") do
    :plain
      = render CharacterComponent.new(name: "Loco") do |character|
        - character.with_weapon(css: "text-primary")
        This hero fights for cleaner templates!

.mt-6.prose
  :markdown
    That's it — parts for structure, slots for content, options for
    configuration, and the full power of Stimulus when you need behavior. Go
    build something!

